<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-839-944  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 839 944.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Sept 3 1990 v4 n32 p10(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Gulf crisis highlights DLA crisis. (Defense Logistics Agency)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Levine, Arnold S.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Everything has been moving like clockwork in the logistics sectorduring the Persian Gulf crisis, with the Military Airlift Command,the Defense Logistics Agency, the services' logistics commands andother Defense Department organizations performing according toplan.andP;  The smooth buildup with 50,000 troops and hundreds ofmillions of dollars worth of material is amazing simply because ofthe organizations involved.andP;  However, the General AccountingOffice has issued numerous reports on the deficiencies of themilitary supply system since the 1970s, arguing that the DODshould manage its inventories the way large retail andmanufacturing companies manage theirs.andP;  Perhaps the DOD's systemis better than the GAO's own evaluation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ManagementInventory ControlInventory EvaluationDisaster PlanningDisaster ManagementReportsUnited States. Department of DefenseUnited States. General Accounting Office.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>